		<div class="w3-half w3-container">
			<h1>What is this research about?</h1>
				<h2> Deciding to criminalize and detain immigrants (including those seeking asylum) generated
        a stream of unwelcome (if unintended) side effects that were fully anticipated. Even before
        the Trump presidency, ICE provided substandard health care. Because ICE failed to provide 
        readily available vaccines, ICE facilities were prone to (avoidable) outbreaks of mumps, flu, and other communicable diseases.
        Given this indifference to the health and well-being of people detained, the exacerbation of COVID-19 transmission
        in and near to ICE facilities was not the result of “error, ignorance, or blindness …. [The question is not why ICE
        officials and U.S. political leaders] failed to anticipate these effects but why, given the foreseen risks, they chose
        to go ahead anyway.”111 We argue that due to the callous cruelty that permeates ICE's policies and procedures, 
        the human, social, and political rights of people seeking to immigrate to the United States were routinely violated.
        This same callousness led ICE to persist in detention policies that gave rise to alarmingly high infection COVID-19 rates in ICE facilities.
				</h2>
		</div>
	</div>
	<hr>
	
	<div class="example w3-row">
		<div class="w3-half w3-container">
			<h1>What did the researchers do?</h1>
				<h2>The researchers located and analyzed academic, government, and non-governmental data to understand 
					the impact of ICE facilities on the community spread of COVID-19. This research examined risks at 
          two spatial scales—specific to ICE facilities and among surrounding 
          communities. At both scales, we highlighted a distinction: the intentions of policy makers 
        and, whether or not unwelcome outcomes were intended, the degree to which policymakers anticipated
        (and permitted) these outcomes. As the Black Lives Movement and critical race literature have 
        documented, racist over-policing and mass incarceration policies were put in place with the 
        intention of intimidating and stigmatizing Black Americans. Although mass incarceration was 
        not designed to facilitate disease transmission, heightened infection rates in overcrowded 
        prisons and jails was well documented long before the COVID-19 pandemic. 
				</h2>
		</div>
		
		<div class="w3-half w3-container">
