		<div class="w3-twothird w3-container">
			<h1>What did the researcher find?</h1>
				<h2>Warmaking drives carbon emissions even in times of global 
					Recession - when the slow-down of the global economy is reducing the impact of gross domestic product on carbon emissions.
					Risk-tranfer militarism in the Global North shifts the attendant risks of war to the peoples and the environments of the 
					Global South. While the Global North is pursuing a strategy that relies on carbon-intensive advanced weaponry,
					the Global South is investing in more boots on the ground. In addition to bearing the brundt of impacts from the Global North's
					asymmetric warfare, the Global South will also be the most impacted by global climate change driven by CO2 emissions.
				</h2><br><br>
					   
				<h2>At a second—and more diffused—spatial scale, ICE facilities were part of the riskscape of surrounding communities and counties.
        The ICE controlled the movement, living conditions, and opportunities for disease mitigation for those detained, whereas ICE did 
        not control public health policy making among nearby communities. At this spatial scale, the concept of blow back offers insights.113 
        When deploying chemical and biological weapons, the intent is to inflict harm on enemy troops.<br><br>
        
        Although generals and admirals cannot prevent the drift of chemical and biological weapons (resulting in casualties and deaths among 
        their own troops), they fully anticipate these unwelcome consequences. In the same vein, the blow back (in this case, an elevated infection
        rate in surrounding communities) that flowed from the spike in COVID-19 infections in ICE facilities was predicted by the people 
        detained by ICE, public health officials, and immigrant advocacy groups.
				</h2>
		</div>
		
	</div>
	<hr>
	<div class="example w3-row">
		<div class="w3-container">
			<h1>How can you use this research?</h1>
			<h2>Governments can be reminded that racist and nativist policies produce blowback. 
			</h2>
